## Fox
- FOX provides electrical isolation between different components on the wafer
- Helps to prevent interference or leakage current
## Bonding Pads
- The bonding pad is the interface between the die and the package (Inputs and Outputs)
- There is one side of the wire soldered to the pad
  While the other is connected to the lead frame
# MOSIS 
- The basic size of the pad specified by MOSIS is
 a square 100 $\mu m \times 100 \space \mu m$
- If u wanted a probe pad(used at microprobe stations for testing) 
  it should be $\gt 6\mu m \times 6\mu m$
- Pads don't scale with process dimensions
## Passivation $\uparrow$
- Since an insulator is covering the pad in the above figure above
- There's no way to bond a wire to it
- This top layer insulator is called passivation
  - It helps protect the chip from contamination
- There are openings (*cuts in the passivation*) 
- In order to place/specify these openings we use and overglass layer
- The MOSIS rules specify 6 um distance between the edge of the metal2 and the overglass box
## Pad Layer
-  Has no fabrication significance 
- But is used to help machines indicate the location of the pads
- Typically (at least for this book) no need to use
- It's assumed where u placed your glass the pad also goes too
