## Parasitic
- Metal layers often create parasitic capacitances and resistances
- Metal layers are characterized by a sheet resistance
   its to be noted that its lower than that of the n-well
- In this book we use a sheet resistance for metal 
   that is $0.1 \ohm /square$
### Example
*Problem*: Estimate the resistance of a piece of metal1 1mm long and 200 nm wide 
*Answer*: $R =\frac{{1 \times 10^-3}}{200 \times 10^-9} \cdot \frac{0.1\ohm}{square} = 500 \ohm$
#### Calculating Capacitance
![[Pasted image 20260422101159.png]]
![[Pasted image 20260422105203.png]]
##### Bottom zero bias capacitance
- $C_{jOb} = (\frac{capacitance}{area}) \cdot (scale)^2 \cdot (bottom \space area)$
##### Sidewall zero-bias depletion capacitance
- $C_{jOs} = (\frac{capacitance}{area}) \cdot (depth \space of \space the \space well) \cdot (perimeter \ of \ the \ well) \cdot (scale)^2$

##### Other
- Depletion Capacitance
is modeled with $C_{j} = \frac{C_{jo}}{\left[ 1-\left( \frac{V_{D}}{V_{bi}} \right) \right]^m}$
- With $C_{jo}$ being zero-bias capacitance of the pn junction
   - When the voltage across the diode is zero
- $V_D$ is the voltage across the diode
- $m$ is the grading coefficient(*showing how the silicon changes from n- to p-type*)
- $V_{bi}$ is the built-in potential
