### Contact resistance
- Anytime a contact with metal is invoked 
   - we also get an inherent resistance with it ( for purposes of this book we use $10 \ohm /contact$ )
    - We can increases the number of vias in order to avoid the 100 $\mu$A of current flowing through a single via  
	   - This also further decreases the voltage drop and in turn the electromigration effects
## Crosstalk/Ground Bounce 
- Crosstalk is just unwanted interference from two conductors
  - Crosstalk is only a problem for time-varying signals
  - When there is two conductors something called mutual capacitance and inductance is induced 
- Ground bounce describes local variations in the power and ground supplies at a circuit
  - Ground bounce can be applied to both time varying signals and dc signals 
![[Pasted image 20260424122016.png]]
### How to determine $C_m$
- We can determine $C_m$ by applying a step voltage to one conductor while measuring the coupled voltage on the adjacent conductor
   - Using that we can write $\triangle V = V_{A} \cdot \frac{C_{m}}{C_{m} + C_{1sub}}$
- $C_{1sub}$ is the capacitance of the adjacent conductor (*metal1 to ground(substrate)*)
+ Remember these lines also exhibit a mutual inductance
   - Current flowing through one induces a voltage on the other 
     - It can be measured by running a current through one inductor and measuring the voltage on the other 
	     - It is measured using $V_m = L_m \frac{dI_{A}}{dt}$
- $I_A$ is the injected (*time varying*) current 
- $V_m$ is the induced voltage 
- Crosstalk can be reduced by increasing distance 
  - Sometimes the designer has no control over this
    - In that case we balance the signals on adjacent conductors
